				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/barredowl" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6001754); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=6001754&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204468" alt="barredowl" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=6001754)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/barredowl" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6001754); return false;" >barredowl</a></span> <span class="odate time_1589640482 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">16 May 2020 14:48</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4650131">
									

<p>This one doesn't really scratch the Parawatch itch for me. A lot of things, I'm not so sure about: for one, I wasn't exactly too scared by this. It doesn't offer anything particularly exciting or new to the Parawatch scene, and multiple parts felt like it was covering the same ground that other pieces such as <a href="/sunday-dinner">Sunday Dinner</a> or <a href="/abwesenheit">Abwesenheit</a> do (although not the most apt comparison, it still reminded me thematically of things like that). Additionally, I'm not too keen on the stinger at the end. Doesn't have much buildup and it didn't have that fridge horror moment a lot of the aforementioned Parawatch tales have. I also have complaints on how it shifts into a first-person story midway through, though that might just be a stylistic choice and I don't find it fair to point it out.</p>
<p><em><strong>EDIT:</strong> At the author's request, I took a second look and liked the ending a lot more. As such, I have changed my vote accordingly.</em></p>

							</div>

								
